# 2. MACHINE LEARNING FUNDAMENTALS (30 pairs)
# =============================================================================

qa_pairs.extend([
    ("How does gradient descent work and what are its security implications?",
     "Gradient descent iteratively adjusts model parameters by computing the gradient of a loss function and moving parameters in the direction that minimizes loss. Security implications include gradient-based adversarial attacks where attackers compute gradients with respect to inputs to craft adversarial examples, and gradient leakage attacks that can reconstruct training data from shared gradients."),

    ("What is backpropagation and how can it be exploited?",
     "Backpropagation computes gradients by applying the chain rule backwards through a neural network, enabling efficient parameter updates. It can be exploited through gradient-based adversarial attacks like FGSM and PGD, and through gradient leakage in federated learning where shared gradients can be inverted to reconstruct private training data."),

    ("How do transformer architectures create unique security challenges?",
     "Transformers process input sequences through self-attention mechanisms that create all-to-all token interactions. Security challenges include prompt injection through attention manipulation, the ability for malicious tokens to influence processing of benign tokens through attention heads, and the difficulty of auditing information flow through multiple attention layers."),

    ("What is the attention mechanism and how does it relate to AI security?",
     "The attention mechanism computes relevance scores between query, key, and value vectors, allowing models to focus on relevant input parts. Security-relevant properties include attention pattern manipulation through adversarial inputs, the potential for attention heads to memorize sensitive training data, and the interpretability of attention weights for understanding model decision-making."),

    ("How do embeddings create security vulnerabilities in AI systems?",
     "Embeddings map discrete inputs to continuous vector spaces where semantic similarity is preserved. Security vulnerabilities include embedding inversion attacks that can recover original text from embedding vectors, poisoning attacks in shared embedding spaces, and membership inference attacks that exploit embedding space geometry to determine training set membership."),

    ("What security risks arise from tokenization in language models?",
     "Tokenization splits text into subword units using algorithms like BPE or SentencePiece. Security risks include token-level adversarial attacks that exploit tokenizer splits, glitch tokens that trigger unexpected model behavior, Unicode-based attacks using visually similar characters that tokenize differently, and prompt injection techniques that exploit tokenization boundaries."),

    ("How do different loss functions affect model robustness?",
     "Loss functions define the optimization objective and directly impact adversarial robustness. Cross-entropy loss can lead to overconfident predictions that adversarial examples exploit, while adversarial training uses modified loss functions incorporating worst-case perturbations. The choice between L1, L2, and Linf norms in adversarial loss functions determines which types of perturbations the model resists."),

    ("What is the role of regularization in preventing overfitting and its security impact?",
     "Regularization techniques like L1/L2 penalties, dropout, and weight decay constrain model capacity to improve generalization. From a security perspective, regularization reduces memorization of training data, mitigating membership inference and data extraction attacks. However, excessive regularization can degrade model performance and make adversarial examples easier to find."),

    ("How do optimization algorithms affect the security of trained models?",
     "Optimization algorithms like SGD, Adam, and AdaGrad determine how models converge to solutions in the loss landscape. Security implications include the finding that SGD with momentum tends to find flatter minima that are more adversarially robust, while adaptive optimizers like Adam can converge to sharper minima that are more vulnerable to small perturbations."),

    ("What is the Fast Gradient Sign Method (FGSM) and why is it significant?",
     "FGSM, proposed by Goodfellow et al. in 2014, generates adversarial examples by adding perturbations in the direction of the gradient's sign, scaled by epsilon. It demonstrated that imperceptible perturbations could cause high-confidence misclassification in neural networks, launching the field of adversarial machine learning and motivating adversarial training as a defense."),

    ("How does Projected Gradient Descent (PGD) improve on FGSM attacks?",
     "PGD is an iterative adversarial attack that applies multiple smaller gradient steps with projection back onto an epsilon-ball around the original input. Proposed by Madry et al. in 2018, it is considered the strongest first-order adversary and forms the basis of adversarial training, producing more effective adversarial examples than single-step FGSM."),

    ("What is model inversion and how does it threaten training data privacy?",
     "Model inversion attacks reconstruct training data features by optimizing inputs to maximize model confidence for a target class. Fredrikson et al. demonstrated in 2015 that facial recognition models could be inverted to reconstruct recognizable face images of training subjects, revealing that deployed models can inadvertently leak sensitive information about their training data."),

    ("How does membership inference attack work against ML models?",
     "Membership inference attacks determine whether a specific data point was in a model's training set by exploiting differences in model behavior on training vs. non-training data. Shokri et al. introduced shadow model techniques in 2017, showing that overfitted models exhibit measurably higher confidence on training examples, enabling privacy violations."),

    ("What are the security implications of transfer learning?",
     "Transfer learning reuses pre-trained model weights for new tasks, but introduces security risks including backdoor transfer where poisoned weights carry malicious behaviors to downstream models. Attackers can publish trojaned pre-trained models on public repositories like Hugging Face, compromising all downstream applications that fine-tune from the poisoned checkpoint."),

    ("How does batch normalization affect adversarial robustness?",
     "Batch normalization normalizes layer activations using batch statistics during training and running statistics during inference. This discrepancy creates vulnerabilities where adversarial examples can exploit batch norm statistics, and research has shown that removing batch normalization or using group normalization can improve adversarial robustness in certain architectures."),

    ("What is the relationship between model capacity and memorization of sensitive data?",
     "Larger models with higher capacity are more prone to memorizing individual training examples, including sensitive data. Carlini et al. demonstrated in 2021 that GPT-2 memorized and could regurgitate verbatim text from its training data, including personal information. This creates a fundamental tension between model performance and privacy protection."),

    ("How do convolutional neural networks differ from transformers in adversarial vulnerability?",
     "CNNs process local spatial features through convolutional filters, making them vulnerable to local adversarial perturbations that exploit spatial invariances. Transformers, processing global token relationships through attention, are vulnerable to different attack vectors including attention pattern manipulation. Research shows transformers can be more robust to certain patch-based attacks but more vulnerable to token-level attacks."),

    ("What is knowledge distillation and what are its security implications?",
     "Knowledge distillation transfers knowledge from a large teacher model to a smaller student model by training the student to match the teacher's soft probability outputs. Security implications include the finding that distilled models can inherit adversarial vulnerabilities from teacher models, and that model extraction attacks essentially perform distillation to steal model functionality."),

    ("How do generative adversarial networks (GANs) create security challenges?",
     "GANs consist of a generator creating synthetic data and a discriminator distinguishing real from fake data. They create security challenges by enabling generation of realistic deepfakes, synthetic identity documents, and adversarial examples. The adversarial training process itself can be unstable, and GANs can memorize training data, potentially leaking sensitive information."),

    ("What is the significance of the Lipschitz constant in adversarial robustness?",
     "The Lipschitz constant bounds how much a function's output can change relative to input changes. Models with smaller Lipschitz constants are inherently more robust to adversarial perturbations because small input changes produce correspondingly small output changes. Techniques like spectral normalization and Lipschitz-constrained training directly improve certified adversarial robustness."),

    ("How do recurrent neural networks handle security-sensitive sequential data?",
     "RNNs, including LSTM and GRU variants, process sequential data by maintaining hidden states across time steps. Security concerns include the potential for long-range information leakage through hidden states, vulnerability to adversarial sequences that exploit temporal dependencies, and the difficulty of applying differential privacy to sequential training data."),

    ("What are the security implications of attention head specialization in transformers?",
     "Research has shown that individual attention heads in transformers specialize for different linguistic functions. Security implications include the possibility that specific heads may be responsible for safety behavior and could be targeted for deactivation, and that attention head analysis can reveal which input tokens most influence model outputs for interpretability and attack design."),

    ("How does the softmax function in neural networks relate to adversarial confidence?",
     "The softmax function converts logits to probability distributions but can produce overconfident predictions even for out-of-distribution inputs. This means adversarial examples can achieve high-confidence misclassifications, and the softmax bottleneck makes it difficult to distinguish adversarial inputs from legitimate ones based on prediction confidence alone."),

    ("What is catastrophic forgetting and how does it affect AI safety?",
     "Catastrophic forgetting occurs when neural networks lose previously learned information upon training on new data. For AI safety, this means safety-aligned behaviors learned during RLHF can be overwritten by fine-tuning on harmful data, as demonstrated by research showing that safety guardrails can be removed with as few as 100 examples of harmful fine-tuning data."),

    ("How do variational autoencoders (VAEs) relate to privacy in generative models?",
     "VAEs encode data into a learned latent distribution and decode samples from that distribution. They offer some privacy advantages over GANs because the latent space structure makes memorization analysis more tractable. However, VAEs can still memorize training examples in low-density regions of the latent space, and the decoder can be attacked to reconstruct sensitive training data."),

    ("What is the role of dropout in defending against model extraction attacks?",
     "Dropout randomly deactivates neurons during training and inference, introducing stochasticity into model predictions. This stochasticity makes model extraction attacks more difficult because the attacker receives inconsistent responses to identical queries. However, averaging multiple queries can overcome dropout-based defenses, making it a limited but complementary defense mechanism."),

    ("How do skip connections in neural networks affect adversarial vulnerability?",
     "Skip connections, as used in ResNet architectures, allow gradients to flow directly through the network, which paradoxically makes gradient-based adversarial attacks more effective. Research shows that models with skip connections are easier to attack because the gradient signal is cleaner, but they can also be easier to adversarially train due to the same gradient flow properties."),

    ("What is the relationship between model quantization and security?",
     "Model quantization reduces precision of model weights from 32-bit floating point to lower bit widths for efficiency. Security implications include the finding that quantized models can exhibit different adversarial vulnerabilities than full-precision counterparts, quantization can inadvertently remove safety guardrails, and the discretization can create new attack surfaces not present in full-precision models."),

    ("How does data augmentation relate to adversarial robustness?",
     "Data augmentation applies transformations like rotation, cropping, and color jittering to training data to improve generalization. While standard augmentation provides limited adversarial robustness, adversarial training is essentially augmentation with adversarial examples. Research shows that combining standard augmentation with adversarial training improves robustness more than either technique alone."),

    ("What is the security significance of neural network pruning?",
     "Neural network pruning removes redundant weights or neurons to reduce model size. Security research has shown that pruning can disproportionately affect model fairness by degrading performance on underrepresented groups, can inadvertently remove safety-critical neurons, and can change adversarial robustness properties unpredictably, sometimes improving and sometimes degrading robustness."),
])

